<div id="review_3092519900" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3092519900" />
    <a title="Alice" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/48775114-alice"><img alt="Alice" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1597603562p2/48775114.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3092519900?book_show_action=true">Dec 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alice" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alice" href="/user/show/48775114-alice">Alice</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48775114-alice?shelf=audiobook">audiobook</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48775114-alice?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3092519900" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8140980211365348454">Sadly, nothing stuck out or engaged me in this book. Given the importance of telling these stories, there always space for new ones, but this one feels like something I’ve already read between the pages of <i>The Kite Runner</i> and Afghan non-fiction.<br/>Unlike other refugees’ recounts, this one didn’t draw me in or get me attached to the fleeing main character. This is probably due to Geda’s bland narration, which really doesn’t enrich Enaiat’s disadventures. The author keeps the reader at a distance as </span>
  <span id="freeText8140980211365348454" style="display:none">Sadly, nothing stuck out or engaged me in this book. Given the importance of telling these stories, there always space for new ones, but this one feels like something I’ve already read between the pages of <i>The Kite Runner</i> and Afghan non-fiction.<br />Unlike other refugees’ recounts, this one didn’t draw me in or get me attached to the fleeing main character. This is probably due to Geda’s bland narration, which really doesn’t enrich Enaiat’s disadventures. The author keeps the reader at a distance as he switches the focus between the interview with the current 20 year old and the perspective of the child he used to be. He doesn’t express effectively the desperation or innocence of a kid escaping his home, therefore might have stuck with a linear interview that wasn’t trying too hard. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8140980211365348454" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


