  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4464302402" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4464302402" />
    <a title="Natalie Shawver" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6157089-natalie-shawver"><img alt="Natalie Shawver" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1324945627p2/6157089.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4464302402?book_show_action=true">Jan 10, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Natalie Shawver" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Natalie Shawver" href="/user/show/6157089-natalie-shawver">Natalie Shawver</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4464302402" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4512689532922570669">When I was 10 years old, I&apos;m pretty sure I was riding my bike outside with the neighborhood gang or reading a book. I wasn&apos;t trekking my way from my home village across multiple countries on my own (with very little money or food), fending for myself. I&apos;m honestly not sure I could have done that ... not sure I&apos;d have either the smarts or the bravery to make that happen. But in 2002, Enaiatollah Akbari’s village fell prey to the Taliban and his mother, fearing for his life, led him across the bor</span>
  <span id="freeText4512689532922570669" style="display:none">When I was 10 years old, I'm pretty sure I was riding my bike outside with the neighborhood gang or reading a book. I wasn't trekking my way from my home village across multiple countries on my own (with very little money or food), fending for myself. I'm honestly not sure I could have done that ... not sure I'd have either the smarts or the bravery to make that happen. But in 2002, Enaiatollah Akbari’s village fell prey to the Taliban and his mother, fearing for his life, led him across the border. (Also not sure I could have done that as a mother ... sent my son out alone in the great big world at 10!)<br /><br />From there began Enaiat's five-year journey through Iran, Turkey, Pakistan, and Greece before he he sought political asylum in Italy (smart kid). As I read each chapter, I was more and more amazed at the resourcefulness and sheer courage of this little boy. He found odd jobs, made friends with children and adults alike, trekked across bitterly cold mountains, rode in the bottom of trucks, steered a raft through violent waters ... all before 15!<br /><br />So began Enaiat’s remarkable and often publishing five-year ordeal—making his way across bitterly cold mountains, riding the suffocating false bottom of a truck, steering an inflatable raft in violent waters—through Iran, Turkey, Pakistan, and Greece, before he eventually sought political asylum in Italy, all before he turned fifteen years old.<br /> <br />Enaiat's true story is captured by Fabio Geda in a conversational tone mixed with humor and intrigue. Enaiat was wise beyond his years. It made me look at my oh-so-comfortable life and realize that many, many have the complete opposite. I never even knew things like this occurred so not only was this book a major eye-opener for me, but it once again reminded me of the human spirit's need to connect with others, overcome obstacles, and have faith along the way. Highly recommend.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4512689532922570669" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


